    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "a2e32149_27efdea2",
        "filename": "client/simple_address_range_bag.h",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 121,
      "author": {
        "id": 1144260
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-02-29T18:49:21Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I started implementing a set originally, and then switched. From the client side, the way this will be used is paired (maybe scoped) add/remove for a certain lifetime while a data structure to be captured is valid. So being able to just unconditionally add/remove seemed simpler.\n\nAnother interface might be to have Insert() return a token/handle, but that sort of boils down to the same thing.",
      "parentUuid": "a20c01ef_999a9b8a",
      "revId": "c24b0ba983be134f99fd8516b8bc859af63cb9fd",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c2e0153f_82505a50",
        "filename": "client/simple_address_range_bag.h",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 121,
      "author": {
        "id": 1143760
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-02-29T19:20:40Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yeah, I thought about the token thing too, I kind of like it, but it’s not too important. Practical users that want paired insert/remove will probably have it wrapped up in an object that does the removal on destruction.\n\nI suppose that as long as we’re deduplicating memory regions when we write the dump anyway, we can just treat this as an implementation detail for now.",
      "parentUuid": "a2e32149_27efdea2",
      "revId": "c24b0ba983be134f99fd8516b8bc859af63cb9fd",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
